  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law on money laundering involves multiple layers of cooperation and legal frameworks:\n\n1. Key International Organizations\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC)\n- International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n\n2. Primary Legal Mechanisms\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Palermo Convention\n- Basel Committee Guidelines\n- FATF Recommendations\n\n3. Typical Intersection Points\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Extradition agreements\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Consistent legal definitions of money laundering\n\n4. National Implementation\n- Countries adapt international standards into domestic legislation\n- Establish financial intelligence units\n- Create regulatory frameworks for banking/financial institutions\n- Implement Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Coordinated investigations\n- Shared intelligence databases\n- Mutual legal support\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n\n6. Challenges\n- Jurisdictional differences\n- Varying legal standards\n- Technology-driven money laundering techniques\n- Complex international financial networks\n\nThese intersections create a complex but increasingly coordinated global approach to combating money laundering.",
